posts.com:
Mi sveglio con il suono del Nessun Dorma di Pavarotti che risuona dal mio grammofono, mentre la mia moglie formosa apre le tende per permettermi di ammirare la torre pendente di Pisa. Mentre scendo i gradini di pietra della fattoria del XIII secolo in cui viviamo, vedo che mia moglie ha già pronto un pacchetto completo per me: un espresso e un pacchetto di sigarette. Lo butto giù in un colpo solo mentre accendo la prima sigaretta e parto con la mia Vespa, pronto per il lavoro. Mentre passo davanti al Colosseo accendo un'altra sigaretta con quella che ho già in bocca e sono pronto per il mio espresso con i colleghi al bar.

Mi registro e sono le 12, quindi è ora di pranzo. Andiamo in trattoria per un pasto di 5 portate: pasta, pasta, grigliata mista, pesce, caffè e ammazzacaffè. Insomma, bisogna tenersi leggeri. Poi è il momento di portare le sigarette a fare una passeggiata in piazza San Marco. 3 espressi dopo siamo di nuovo in ufficio, facciamo 30 minuti di lavoro ed è il momento della sigaretta di metà pomeriggio, ma questa volta andiamo in terrazza per ammirare la splendida vista del Vesuvio.

È poi l'ora dell'aperitivo. Torniamo sulla Vespa, sfrecciamo davanti alla Galleria degli Uffizi mentre fumiamo ed ecco un bel piatto misto di salumi mentre aspettiamo che mia moglie, dalle tette generose, prepari la cena.

Poi è il momento della pizza, di 3/4 bottiglie di vino, del limoncello e tutti gridano che dovrei tirare fuori il mandolino ed eseguire l'ultimo successo, o' Sole mio. La folla si scatena, lancia le sigarette in aria ed è ora di andare a letto. Scendiamo tutti con il nostro amaro e loro si avviano verso le loro lambrette. A questo punto è il momento di uno spuntino prima di andare a letto, magari di una sigaretta mentre i meloni enormi di mia moglie oscillano mentre pulisce la casa e mi dà il bacio della buonanotte.

E così mi addormento, pensando a domani, quando inizieranno i 3 mesi di vacanza imposti dal governo. La vita è bella.

Lanciava maledizioni a chi non le dava l'elemosina all'uscita dalla chiesa: 52enne arrestata
TRIESTE - Lanciava maledizioni a chi non le dava l'elemosina all'uscita della Chiesa di Isernia. Si tratta di una 52enne romena che con tutto il suo clan si era trasferita in un campo della vicina provincia occupandosi dei bambini e chiedendo qualche moneta sul sagrato della chiesa. Nella sua nuova vita era arrivato anche l’amore, perché nel campo aveva conosciuto anche un giovane di cui si era innamorata. Tuttavia, il suo atteggiamento nel chiedere la carità era troppo invadente e insistente, perché quando non riusciva a ottenere una moneta lanciava qualche maledizione ai fedeli in uscita dal luogo di culto. E così la donna era stata allontanata dal comune con un provvedimento di foglio di via obbligatorio. La 52enne lo aveva violato per stare vicina al suo amore, e per questo ha iniziato a collezionare delle denunce. Poi col tempo anche l’amore era svanito.

Nel suo nuovo tragitto è stata controllata dalla pattuglia della Radiomobile di Aurisina mentre viaggiava su un autobus diretto in Sicilia. I militari hanno scoperto che era ricercata per un mandato di cattura, dovendo scontare 1 mese di reclusione per aver violato il divieto di ritorno nel comune di Isernia per fatti commessi nel 2010. E' stata arrestata e portata al carcere del Coroneo.

“Vado ad ucciderla”, 15enne sente parlare al telefono un uomo sul treno e lo fa arrestare: sventato femminicidio
Ha 15 anni il ragazzino che, complice la stessa lingua e il coraggio, ha sventato un femminicidio. La storia arriva da Modena, dove un 30enne di origine rumena aveva pianificato di arrivare in treno con l’obiettivo di uccidere la donna conosciuta in una chat di incontri.
Lei, sua connazionale residente a Carpi, gli aveva dato appuntamento per lo scorso sabato 17 dicembre salvo poi fare marcia indietro quando il 30enne aveva iniziato a comportarsi in modo insistente e aggressivo. Da lì l’inizio dell’ossessione, la persecuzione a suon di offese e minacce e addirittura un video inviatole in cui mostrava il coltello da cucina che avrebbe utilizzato per ammazzarla.

Il giorno del non-appuntamento la decisione di andare lo stesso a Modena: il 30enne, come racconta un articolo del Corriere di Bologna, sale su un treno regionale ma si addormenta, finendo per saltare la stazione di piazza Dante e finendo a Fiorenzuola, nel Piacentino. Qui prende un altro treno per tornare indietro e raggiungere la sua meta ed è a questo punto che interviene il 15enne.

Anche lui rumeno, ascolta le telefonate del 30enne che sempre più nervoso parla con alcuni suoi conoscenti e rivela la sua intenzione di uccidere la donna che lo ha respinto.

L’adolescente, capite le intenzioni del suo connazionale, chiama i Carabinieri e traduce quanto captato della telefonata: i militari allertano la Polfer e appena il treno ferma a Modena ad attendere il 30enne sono gli agenti.

Addosso, dopo averlo identificato e fermato, gli trovano un coltello da cucina e un altro attrezzo a punta. L’uomo è stato quindi fermato con l’accusa di tentato omicidio, con l’arresto convalidato dal giudice che ha disposto la custodia cautelare in carcere per la pericolosità del 30enne e il rischio di reiterare il reato.

Buenos días, colegas del metal. Espero que hayáis tenido una buena mañana.
Ya que os interesa os lo cuento. Mi virginidad sigue intacta, no hubo ni el más mínimo ápice de éxito real.
Lo de la chica que me gusta tuvo dos desarrollos.
El primero es que ayer jugamos al juego de la moneda, no sé si lo conocéis. Si no lo explico en un segundo.
Persona A le hace una pregunta en secreto a Persona B que involucre a todos los presentes en el grupo. Entonces B tiene que darle la moneda a quien supone su respuesta, que es Persona C. C tiene que tirar la moneda; si sale cruz nada, si sale cara B tiene que revelar qué fue lo que le preguntó A.
A mí me pasó lo siguiente. A me preguntó a quién me follaría del grupo, y yo le di la moneda a la chica que me gusta. Salió cara y tuve que decir qué era lo que me habían preguntado. El segundo desarrollo, sin embargo, sucedió hace una semana, justo el día que os dije que iba a ir a por ella en serio. Although Ahmet's journey was far from easy, he learned to manage his schizophrenia and embrace his unique identity. He may have believed himself to be Greek, but to those who knew and loved him, he was simply Ahmet - a kind and quirky man who was loved by all.

It was a typical day in the Byzantine Empire when news of a new conflict with the Bulgarian Kingdom reached the ears of Emperor Constantine. As he sat on his throne, surrounded by his advisors, he couldn't believe what he was hearing.

But as it turned out, the Bulgarians had become fed up with the constant bickering and backstabbing within the Byzantine court, and had decided to declare war in an effort to bring some much-needed unity to the region.

As the conflict raged on, the Byzantine army found itself struggling to keep up with the Bulgarian soldiers. They were well-trained and fiercely determined, and it seemed like no matter what the Byzantines did, they just couldn't get the upper hand.

He summoned his court jester, a lovable fool by the name of Chuckles, and tasked him with the responsibility of infiltrating the Bulgarian camp and sabotaging their plans from within.

At first, Chuckles was skeptical of the plan. "But Your Majesty, I am just a simple jester," he protested. "I have no training in espionage or warfare."

To the surprise of everyone, Chuckles proved to be a natural at espionage. He easily slipped into the Bulgarian camp and began causing chaos wherever he went. He told bad jokes, played pranks, and generally made a nuisance of himself, all while gathering valuable intelligence for the Byzantine army.

In the end, Chuckles' antics proved to be the deciding factor in the war. The Bulgarians, fed up with his constant pranks and jokes, called for a ceasefire and agreed to peace talks. And as the two sides came together to sign a treaty, Chuckles was hailed as a hero and given a medal for his service.

As he returned to the Byzantine court, Chuckles couldn't help but feel a sense of pride. He had never thought he would be capable of such great things, but it seemed that in the midst of war, even the most unlikely of heroes can rise to the occasion.

Ikiboon had always been a bit of an oddball. As a schizophrenic virgin manlet of Turkish descent living in a ghetto in Germany and surviving on welfare, he had never quite fit in with the rest of society. But on this particular Christmas Eve, Ikiboon was feeling especially out of sorts.

As he sat in his cramped and cluttered apartment, staring out the window at the falling snow, Ikiboon couldn't help but think about how different his life could have been. His mother, who had always struggled with mental health issues, had tried to abort him on Christmas Day all those years ago. And now, here he was, a lonely and misunderstood man living on the fringes of society.

But despite his struggles, Ikiboon had always held onto a glimmer of hope. He convinced himself that he was actually Greek, descended from the ancient warriors and philosophers of ancient times. It was a belief that gave him a sense of purpose and pride, even in the darkest of moments.

As the hours ticked by and the snow continued to fall, Ikiboon found himself lost in a world of his own making. He spent the day cooking elaborate Greek dishes and reciting passages from Homer's "The Odyssey," all while trying to ignore the constant chatter in his head.

But just when Ikiboon thought he couldn't take it anymore, there was a knock at the door. He hesitated for a moment, wondering if he should answer or pretend he wasn't home. But then, with a sense of bravery he didn't know he possessed, he opened the door to find a group of his neighbors standing on the other side.

To Ikiboon's surprise, they had come to invite him to join them for Christmas dinner. It was a simple gesture, but it meant the world to him. And as he sat at the table, surrounded by the warmth and laughter of his community, he realized that he wasn't alone after all.

Here he was, a schizophrenic virgin manlet of Turkish descent living in Germany, convinced that he was Greek, and his neighbors had brought him doner kebabs for Christmas dinner.

In that moment, Ikiboon realized that it didn't matter where he came from or what he believed. All that mattered was the love and acceptance of those around him. And as he raised a glass of ouzo to his lips, he couldn't help but feel grateful for the life he had been given, no matter how difficult it may have been.

posts.com:
W 2003 roku stado nieczystych knurów zniosło post w Wigilię Bożego Narodzenia. I dlatego też w Polsce w Wigilię Bożego Narodzenia poszczą normalni ateiści, alkoholicy, więźniowie, i kibice.

Pości dr Stanisław Krajski wraz z kotami i arcybiskupem Lengą. Prawdopodobnie pościł będzie Ks. Jochemczyk, a nawet Ks. Jacek Bałemba i Proboszcz ze Szczecina. Pościć będzie zielona lewica, Ziemie Odzyskane, Dolny Śląsk i pornograficzna prawica. Jest to wyraz świętego oburzenia i nieposłuszeństwa wobec stada nieczystych knurów z Episkopatu, którzy próbują się uwłaszczać na polskiej Tradycji Katolickiej i obyczajach jak knury na trzodzie sobie podległej. Mamy dość tych kabanów, chcemy pasterzy i Bożego Narodzenia takiego, jakie obchodzili nasi polscy święci ojcowie, o których mówi Ksiądz Skarga, Ojciec Prokop i Ks. Gapczyński.

Wierni Rodacy, szukajmy prawdziwych obyczajów Bożego Narodzenia, a rządy zboczeńców będą nam odebrane, gdyż Bóg się rodzi, moc truchleje.

posts.com:
How many papers I can read in a single day? Well, I think I reached my max around a christmas holiday some years ago, when I read about 40 papers and about 50–60 abstracts in single day, plus probably about a hundred wikipedia pages to cover whatever term I encountered and didn’t quite comprehend. And yes then I had to stop, fire up a game and shoot zombies because my brain was melting. It was a twelve hour sit.

It really depends on what field of science you are researching; if you research physics and mathematics I seriously doubt that you will ever reach this kind of speed, because those kind of papers are very, very meaty when it comes to information density. On the other hand, social sciences aren’t particularly meaty when it comes to information, so for a trained reader I think these kinds of numbers are reachable: after all you are after understanding and wisdom instead of just nitpicky trying to analyse every single word or sentence.

I read in biochemistry and medicine, have read well over 10.000 papers this way, and can go through dozens of papers a day, each day, for weeks on time until I get fed up with it.

I was diagnosed with Crohn’s disease in back in 2000, and I literally read my way into it until I figured out enough of the basic disease mechanism to fix it. (and yes the whole of the medical community still hasn’t got a clue…partly because it’s pharmaceuticals that are part of the cause of Crohn’s, and the medical profession tends to be as blind as a bat to faults of their own).

Same thing goes with Covid-19; I contracted covid-19 in march 2020, and was refused treatment because my test were negative and I didn’t have a fever. But the pain in my chest and about a gazillion other bizarre symptoms made it quite, quite clear that I was in serious danger. I also live alone, and if you get the official advise to ‘only call the emergency number if you have difficulty breathing’ …with that same advice apparently unable to answer the question as how to make a telephone call when you can’t breathe. (I ’m not exactly impressed by the medical community at this point)

So, In march and april, I read well over a thousand papers. Because I had to; based on my experience with Crohn’s, I knew that the ability of the medical community to come up with meaningful answers is round about zero, and I could die if I left it over to them.

(You probably find all this doubtful, but I don’t care at this point. So many things in my life are absurd to others that I stopped caring about the word ‘impossible’. It’s a word used by people who never have been pushed far enough to be forced to redefine it’s meaning)

-19 from sciencedirect

-74 from National Center for Biotechnology Information

posts.name: Anonymous

>>175477234
It's not that they gave it up, it's that their entire civilization collapsed. Copper requires a huge technological investment on top of having an agricultural civilization, and no in North America outside of Mesoamerica had that because of the collapse of prior agricultural civilizations (most likely stemming from agricultural failures due to the lack of draft animals acting as plows). For comparison, the Mississippian culture was smelting copper, but the Ojibwe in Ontario/Michigan were just using native copper that they found. Imagine how bizarre copper metallurgy must have been to these people "There are these rocks, right, and if you get them REALLY FUCKING HOT they turn into liquid, and then when they solidfy you get this weird substance that's stiff, but also flexible, and you can hit it really hard to make it change shape, into sharp edges and points".

>>175477354
The Aztec had metalworking, they just never replaced obsidian and flint for blades. And why would you, when obsidian is exponentially sharper than copper or bronze?

For comparison, Europeans were technically still using paleolithic technology into the 1960s, as the flint used in musket ignition systems had to be knapped. It only went away relatively recently, it just became increasingly peripheral.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>175477535
There's some evidence of bronzeworking in Mesoamerica. Presumably it never got off the ground for exactly the reason that you pointed out. Most metalworking in Mesoamerica appears to have been for luxury goods or specialized instruments (such as surgical tools), because, again, obsidian is just so much sharper.

To be clear, the Ojibwe in the Great Lakes region never smelted copper, they just cold-hammered native copper (that is, metallic copper in the ground). Mesoamericans, the Mississippians, and a few other sites actually smelted it, however. There's some evidence of the Inuit using iron for tool heads that they got from meteorites, however. It's not quite Mordor Theory like in Africa, but it's still novel.

In Europe and the Middle East, stone tools were used ubiquitously until about 2000BC, where they then dwindled to a peripheral position until about 1000BC. Around 2000BC copper working seems to have taken off. The earliest sites of copper working are in Serbia circa 5000BC, but who knows if they got it from somewhere else. Copper working was, across Europe and the Middle East, a very technical trade that had connotations of foreignness. Around 1500-1200BC, however, economic downturns made getting copper and tin/arsenic (which, typically, are nowhere near each other) via trade very difficult. In Eastern Europe circa 1000BC iron working appears to start up. It then starts popping up throughout Europe. Unlike copper and tin/arsenic, iron is everywhere. It's not very high quality, but it's easily sourced, and more importantly, you don't have to get it via trade. Ironworking, unlike copperworking, develops as a mystical, native art, as everywhere starts figuring it out all at once, rather than travelling experts diffusing it. This basically happens along the same timeline in China.

In Africa, none of that happened. Somewhere between 1500BC and 1000BC, in southern central Africa, they suddenly got ironworking, with no copper intermediary. Interestingly, because they never figured out quenching or hammer-hardening, they ended up just making increasingly better furnaces and heating techniques until they were creating a sort of wrought steel (by today's standards it's shit, but for the time it wouldn't be surpassed until thousands of years later, albeit by people who were using a far more efficient set of techniques).
